o threaten their holdings in the Atlantic Ocean. In the years since, white elites in Cuba, the Dominican Republic, and Puerto Rico upheld Haiti as a symbol of barbarism and savagery. Racialized Visions powerfully refutes this symbolism. Across twelve essays, contributors demonstrate how cultural producers in these countries have resignified Haiti to mean liberation. An introduction and conclusion by the editor, Vanessa K. Valdés, as well as foreword by Myriam J. A. Chancy, provide valuable historical context and an overview of Afro-Latinx studies and its futures.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aBlacks in literature. 0aBlackszWest IndiesxSocial conditions. 0aCaribbean literature (Spanish)xHaitian influences. 0aCaribbean literature (Spanish)xHistory and criticism. 0aRace in literature. 0aRacismzWest IndiesxHistory. 4aAfrican American Studies : Black Studies. 4aCultural Studies : Cultural Studies. 4aHistory : History. 4aLatin American, Caribbean, and Latinx Studies : Caribbean Studies. 4aLiterature : Literary Criticism. 7aHISTORY / Caribbean & West Indies / General.2bisacsh1 aAccilien, Cécile, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCastro, Ángela, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChancy, Myriam J. A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDelné, Claudy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFetus, Mohwanah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGibson, Carrie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKaisary, Philip, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLéger, Natalie Marie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPast, Mariana, econtributor.4ctb4https:/